<div id="review_29094225" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/29094225" />
    <a title="♥ Ibrahim ♥ " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1178748-ibrahim"><img alt="♥ Ibrahim ♥ " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619626524p2/1178748.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/29094225?book_show_action=true">Aug 02, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="♥ Ibrahim ♥ " class="user" itemprop="url" name="♥ Ibrahim ♥ " href="/user/show/1178748-ibrahim">♥ Ibrahim ♥ </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1178748-ibrahim?shelf=thinkers-i-adore">thinkers-i-adore</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1178748-ibrahim?shelf=spirituality">spirituality</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer29094225" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16210361105147458386">I wish I had read Thây (Thích) long time ago! The only reason I didn&apos;t read him is because I was afraid of his Buddhist views while claiming to be open-minded,etc. This book is a gem and is a book to keep and refer to over and over again. It begins where one is, with basically very little knowledge of how to &quot;breathe&quot; and be mindful. These breathing techniques are currently being used as excellent tools by doctors and are proven to work very well in lowering blood pressure, etc. Take a look here</span>
  <span id="freeText16210361105147458386" style="display:none">I wish I had read Thây (Thích) long time ago! The only reason I didn't read him is because I was afraid of his Buddhist views while claiming to be open-minded,etc. This book is a gem and is a book to keep and refer to over and over again. It begins where one is, with basically very little knowledge of how to "breathe" and be mindful. These breathing techniques are currently being used as excellent tools by doctors and are proven to work very well in lowering blood pressure, etc. Take a look here for instance:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/09/breathing-health_n_3696302.html?utm_hp_ref=mostpopular">http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08...</a><br />You read the book and you come to discover that the book is so easy and it reads by itself and, most importantly, it is practical manual for daily living: learning to watch, to follow one's breath and be a master of one's one mind instead of being passively resigned to negative emotions that might assail us from time to time. We learn to enjoy what we are doing for its own sake, not as a "means" but it is both a subject and an object at the same time. For instance, I don't wash the dishes and get done so I could do something else more fun but I will enjoy what I am doing in the present moment for what it is, and so I will be washing the dishes just to wash the dishes and I will be aware of myself and what I am doing as if it is the only things in my entire life. Chapter 2 is really excellent and I read it several times because it gives gradual, basic and advanced breathing exercises. Anybody can do these exercises anytime they want and not be intimidated. He explains all that as if he is talking to you and speaking to your heart. Towards the end of the book, it has many exercises in mindfulness and a selection of Buddhist sutras so we get to taste their own texts in their own context and in the original Eastern ancient spirit. A pdf copy of this book is available for free download on <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://terebess.hu/zen/mesterek/Thich%20Nhat%20Hanh%20-%20The%20Miracle%20of%20Mindfulness.pdf">https://terebess.hu/zen/mesterek/Thic...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="16210361105147458386" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


