<div id="review_3549535064" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3549535064" />
    <a title="December" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/115129847-december"><img alt="December" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589372152p2/115129847.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3549535064?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="December" class="user" itemprop="url" name="December" href="/user/show/115129847-december">December</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3549535064" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3924874636494077642">Mindfulness and meditation are, contrary to what many in the West may think, more than sitting quietly on the floor and staring into nothingness for 30 minutes a day. They are a way of life, a way of framing and contextualizing yourself, your actions and existence in a different way. <br/>Since this was originally a letter from one Buddhist monk to another, many of the things described are not viable for a Western 40+ hour workday and lifestyle. However, the principles and foundations are still valua</span>
  <span id="freeText3924874636494077642" style="display:none">Mindfulness and meditation are, contrary to what many in the West may think, more than sitting quietly on the floor and staring into nothingness for 30 minutes a day. They are a way of life, a way of framing and contextualizing yourself, your actions and existence in a different way. <br />Since this was originally a letter from one Buddhist monk to another, many of the things described are not viable for a Western 40+ hour workday and lifestyle. However, the principles and foundations are still valuable resources for everyone interested in the topic, and even small changes can make a big difference in a hectic, aggressive lifestyle.<br />The simple language betrays the depths of its content. Just like the allegorical story included in later chapters, most paragraphs are invitations to dwell on their meaning for much longer than it takes to process the mere words.<br />I am neither a religious nor a spiritual person, but I find a deep, calming value in many of the teaching and exercises described in this book and can easily appropriate them to enrich my own mindset. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3924874636494077642" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


